{"id":"4W3i2hyrJTVfcLq85rWgduVQ3y3BMzrSD4pVUCMqPpFhmXWpqxQ","title":"Hacker News: Front Page","displayTitle":"HN Front","url":"https://hnrss.org/frontpage?points=75","feedLink":"https://news.ycombinator.com/","isQuery":false,"isEmpty":false,"isHidden":false,"items":[{"title":"Disco Elysium Explorer","url":"http://134.0.119.41/","date":1736737897,"author":"kelseyfrog","unread":true,"content":"\n<p>Article URL: <a href=\"http://134.0.119.41\">http://134.0.119.41</a></p>\n<p>Comments URL: <a href=\"https://news.ycombinator.com/item?id=42679679\">https://news.ycombinator.com/item?id=42679679</a></p>\n<p>Points: 159</p>\n<p># Comments: 75</p>\n","flags":null,"enclosureUrl":"","enclosureMime":""},{"title":"How did they make cars fall apart in old movies (2017)","url":"https://movies.stackexchange.com/questions/79161/how-did-they-make-cars-fall-apart-in-old-movies","date":1736732512,"author":"mgsouth","unread":true,"content":"\n<p>Article URL: <a href=\"https://movies.stackexchange.com/questions/79161/how-did-they-make-cars-fall-apart-in-old-movies\">https://movies.stackexchange.com/questions/79161/how-did-they-make-cars-fall-apart-in-old-movies</a></p>\n<p>Comments URL: <a href=\"https://news.ycombinator.com/item?id=42679127\">https://news.ycombinator.com/item?id=42679127</a></p>\n<p>Points: 141</p>\n<p># Comments: 49</p>\n","flags":null,"enclosureUrl":"","enclosureMime":""},{"title":"Show HN: Doom (1993) in a PDF","url":"https://doompdf.pages.dev/doom.pdf","date":1736729443,"author":"vk6","unread":true,"content":"\n<p>I made a Doom source port that runs within a PDF file.<p>I was inspired by the recent HN post about Tetris in a PDF (<a href=\"https://news.ycombinator.com/item?id=42645218\">https://news.ycombinator.com/item?id=42645218</a>) and I wondered if I could get Doom to run using a similar method.<p>It turns out that old versions of Emscripten can compile C to asm.js code that will happily run inside the limited JS runtime of the PDF engine. I used the doomgeneric (<a href=\"https://github.com/ozkl/doomgeneric\">https://github.com/ozkl/doomgeneric</a>) fork of the original Doom source, as that made writing the IO fairly easy. All I had to do was implement a framebuffer and keyboard inputs.<p>Unlike previous interactive PDF demos, the output for DoomPDF is achieved by creating a text field for each row of pixels in the screen, then setting their contents to various ASCII characters. This gives me a 6 color monochrome display, that can be updated reasonably quickly (80ms per frame).<p>The source code is available at: <a href=\"https://github.com/ading2210/doompdf\">https://github.com/ading2210/doompdf</a><p>Note that this PDF can only run in Chromium-based browsers that use the PDFium engine.</p>\n<hr>\n<p>Comments URL: <a href=\"https://news.ycombinator.com/item?id=42678754\">https://news.ycombinator.com/item?id=42678754</a></p>\n<p>Points: 272</p>\n<p># Comments: 54</p>\n","flags":null,"enclosureUrl":"","enclosureMime":""},{"title":"Standard patterns in choice-based games (2015)","url":"https://heterogenoustasks.wordpress.com/2015/01/26/standard-patterns-in-choice-based-games/","date":1736728522,"author":"Ariarule","unread":true,"content":"\n<p>Article URL: <a href=\"https://heterogenoustasks.wordpress.com/2015/01/26/standard-patterns-in-choice-based-games/\">https://heterogenoustasks.wordpress.com/2015/01/26/standard-patterns-in-choice-based-games/</a></p>\n<p>Comments URL: <a href=\"https://news.ycombinator.com/item?id=42678647\">https://news.ycombinator.com/item?id=42678647</a></p>\n<p>Points: 174</p>\n<p># Comments: 42</p>\n","flags":null,"enclosureUrl":"","enclosureMime":""},{"title":"The Free Movie: Frame-by-frame, handrawn reproduction of \"The Bee Movie\" (2023)","url":"https://thefreemovie.buzz/","date":1736728020,"author":"gaws","unread":true,"content":"\n<p>Article URL: <a href=\"https://thefreemovie.buzz/\">https://thefreemovie.buzz/</a></p>\n<p>Comments URL: <a href=\"https://news.ycombinator.com/item?id=4267858